# UDS Diagnostic Tool System Architecture
## Ideas
- Could use STM32MP157 series with the LCD touchscreen for functionality so no connection to a laptop or computer is needed.
	- Need USB-C cable, USB-A to micro B cable 
	- MicroSD card with at least 1 GB
- "Â ![Image](data:image/jpeg;base64,)Hi Dan. Here is the setup we are sending to you. You will only have to plug in the power supply and connect a CAN measurement device to the yellow and green banana plug. The current ECA is the device with the orange sticker. When it is plugged in it will send J1939 UDS commands when first powered."
![[Pasted image 20250415160856.png]]
	- 0B source means brake controller
	- When i plug ECA in, a couple of UDS command DA00p is packaging 1939  
		 - 18DA identifier for diagnostic request on uds, bytes are specifying what command 
		 - f1 is source address (diagnostic tool), 0B is destination
		 - DAxx xx is destination
		 - 
	 - Goal is hardware to easily connect and reprogram
		 - flexibly update and reprogram for non programs 
		 - just generate an 8 byte message from same identifier, destination flexible, and source will always f1, destination should be programmable, 8 bytes content 
		 - type in the content of those 8 bytes, all of uds services are defined (read voltage eeprom), want to be able to change content in byte to start, like esc calibration
		 - read can traffic CAN 500 kbaud
		 - generate second message from the bottom and  manually change the 8-bytes sent
	 - start with generating ECU 241
	 - send identifier and then 8 bytes
		 - want ability to read and see there is a response
## Plan
1. Set up development environment in NixOS
	1. First added these lines of code to my `configuration.nix`
	```nix
	nixpkgs.config.allowUnfree = true;
	programs.nix-ld.enable = true;
	programs.nix-ld.libraries = with pkgs; [pkgs.glibc]
	```
	added this to enable the binary file (executable) for the `hello-world` sample to run according to nix.dev that explains how to run non-nix executables
	2. Created directory `stm32mp1-obduds-tool`
		1. In this directory we made a few subdirectories that included `nix/shell.nix`, `firmware` which included application code
		2. `shell.nix` defines a Nix shell that provides the [[Zephyr SDK]] toolchain and it's necessary build tools according to docs.zephyr and Python packages for west/zephyr. West is the build system for Zephyr.
			1. The [[Cortex-M4]] firmware will be built using Zephyr's standard CMake build system [[west]] and [[Ninja]], **not bare-metal**, so we can leverage Zephyr's threads, drivers (CAN, OpenAMP, etc.) and RTOS features.
			2. `shell.nix:`
			 ```nix
			{ pkgs ? import <nixpkgs> {} }:

			# Defining Zephyr SDK version and fetching it
			let
				zephyrSDKVersion = " 0.17.0"; # Latest Zephyr SDK
				zephyrSdk = pkgs.fetchurl {
						url = "https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos/sdk-ng/releases/download/v${zephyrSdkVersion}/zephyr-sdk-${zephyrSdkVersion}_linux-x86_64.tar.xz";
						sha256 = "1qb9idxlwdfnfl0r98ih607czi56kl33j6cwxzacz2gng546nlz7";
					};

			# Derivation to unpack the Zephyr SDK archive into $out
			zephyrSDKUnpacked = pkgs.stdenv.mkDerivation
			{
				name = "zephtr-sdk-${zephyrSdkVersion}";
				src = zephyrSdk;
				buildInputs = [ pkgs.libarchive pkgs.glibc pkgs.makeWrapper pkgs.autoPatchelfHook ]; # Dependencies for unpacking
				phases = [ "installPhase" ];
					installPhase = ''
						mkdir -p $out
						echo "Extracting Zephyr SDK..."
						tar -xf $src -C $out --strip-components=1
						for bin in $out/aarch64-zephyr-elf/bin/*; do
							wrapProgram "$bin" --prefix LD_LIBRARY_PATH : "${pkgs.glibc}/lib";
							# only run patchelf on ELF binaries
							if file "$bin" | grep -q "ELF"; 
								then patchelf --set-interpreter "$(cat $NIX_GLIBC_DYNAMIC_LINKER)" "$bin"
							else
								echo "Skipping $bin"
							fi
						done
						'';
				
			};
			in pkgs.mkShell {
				buildInputs = [
					pkgs.cmake # CMake build system
					pkgs.ninja # Ninja build tool for Zephyr
					pkgs.dtc # Device Tree Compiler
					pkgs.gnumake # Make build tool
					pkgs.gperf # Required for code generation in Zephyr
					pkgs.ccache # Caching compiler
					pkgs.python3 # Python 3 interpreter
					pkgs.steam-run
				]
				++ (with pkgs.python3Packages; [
					west # Zephyrs meta-tool for managing Zephyr projects
					pyelftools # For Zephyr to parse ELF binaries
					pykwalify # For device tree validation
					pyyaml # YAML parser for Zephyr


					packaging # Used by west or Zephyr to build scripts
					progress # Used by west for progress bar
					psutil # Used by some Zephyr scripts

					intelhex # Intel HEX file support (for DFU/flashing utilities)
					
					# Other dependencies can be added in future like canopen, openamp, etc.
				])
				++ [ zephyrSDKUnpacked ]; # Zephyr SDK (cross compiler, toolchains, etc.)

				shellHook = ''
					export ZEPHYR_TOOLCHAIN_VARIANT=zephyr
					export ZEPHYR_SDK_INSTALL_DIR=${zephyrSDKUnpacked}
					'';
					}
				
			```
			3. This `shell.nix` fetches the Zephyr SDK and unpacks it into the Nix store. The SDK is then used to build the firmware.
			4. Set `ZEPHYR_TOOLCHAIN_VARIANT=zephyr` and `ZEPHYR_SDK_INSTALL_DIR` to point to that location.
			5. Includes **[[CMake]]** and **[[Ninja]]** which Zephyr's build system [[west]] requires.
			6. Includes [[device tree compiler]] **[[dtc]]**, which Zephyr uses to compile devicetree source files.
			7. Added [[Python 3]] and the **west** tool from PyPI to the environment along with Python libraries that Zephyrs build scripts need like [[YAML]] parsing. All these corresponding to Zephyrs `requirements.txt` file.
			8. Included [[gperf]] (used by Zephyr for generating lookup tables for Bluetooth and other subsystems) and [[ccache]] (optional, but speeds up builds by caching compiler output).
			9. In future could consider adding OpenOCD or other flash tools for flashing the firmware. Typically for STM32MP1, the M4 firmware is loaded by Linux or via U-Boot.
		3. After doing this tou can enter the dev environment by running in the project root
			```zsh
			export NIXPKGS_ALLOW_UNFREE=1               
			nix-shell nix/shell.nix
			```
			1. This will give you a shell with the necessary tools to build the firmware. (May take awhile the first time, especially with the Zephyr SDK)
2. Next I initialized Zephyr workspace with West
	```zsh
	west init -l firmware
	```
	1. This is telling west to initialize a Zephyr workspace using the manifest 
	2. The manifest in `firmware/west.yml` will specify Zephyr's git repo and revision:
		```zsh
		manifest:
  version: "1.2" # Manifest format version

  defaults:
    remote: zephyr # Default remote for projects
    revision: v3.5.0

  remotes:
    - name: zephyr
      url-base: https://github.com/zephyrproject-rtos

  projects:
    - name: zephyr
      path: zephyr

  self:
    path: .
		```
	3. Then we fetched Zephyr and modules by running
	```zsh
	west update
	```
	4. This downloads the Zephyr RTOS source code and any modules defined in west.yml
	5. To verify that the build environment works I built a sample:
	```zsh
	west build -b stm32mp157c_dk2 zephyr/samples/hello_world
	```
	6. If set up correctly, this build should produce an ELF binary.
3. Now [[stm32mp157f-dk2]] has 2 CAN-FD controllers on-chip and a mailbox [[IPCC]] hardware for [[inter-processor communication]] between A7 and M4 cores. We need to enable these through device tree
![[Pasted image 20250416160122.png]]
![[Pasted image 20250416160333.png]]
	1. By default Zephyr board file does NOT enable the CAN controllers (marked status = disabled in the devicetree) and uses a RAM console instead of a UART (since UART3 is shared with Linux).
	2. Need to enable and configure CAN and set up OpenAMP for IPC (using mailbox and shared memory for RPMsg).
	3. when i run `cd zephyr/boards/arm/stm32mp157c_dk2/` it takes me to the directory where i want to make the overlay file where I will activate the CAN nodes and configure the pins and also ensure IPM mailboxs is open for OpenAMP.
4. Overlay file:
	```dts
	// stm32mp157c_dk2.overlay
	/{
		/* Reserved 32KB for OpenAMP shared memory at 0x1005000 */
		reserved_memory: reserved-memory {
			#address-cells = <1>; // 1 cell for address
			#size-cells = <1>; // 1 cell for size
			ranges; // what ranges does is it reserves the memory region
			ipc_shm_reserved: memory@1005000 {
				reg = <0x1005000 0x8000>; // 32KB at 0x10050000
				no-map; // don't map this region
				
			};
		};

		chosen {
			/* Choose the reserved memory region for OpenAMP */
			zephyr,ipc = &mailbox; /* IPCC mailbox for OpenAMP IPC */
			zephyr,ipc-shm = &ipc_shm_reserved; /* Shared memory for OpenAMP */ 
		};
	};

	/* Enable CAN1 and CAN2 */
	&fdcan1 {
		pinctrl-names = "default". "sleep"
		/* PA11 = FDCAN1_RX, PA12 = FDCAN1_TX (Alternate Function 9 (AF9)) */
		pinctrl-0 = <&can1_rx_pa11 &can1_tx_pa12>;

		/* Configure pins as analog in sleep mode */
		pinctrl-1 = <&can1_sleep_pa11 &can1_sleep_pa12>;

		status = "okay"; /* Enable CAN1 */
	};	
	&fdcan2 {
		pinctrl-names = "default", "sleep"
		/* PB12 = FDCAN2_RX, PB13 = FDCAN2_TX (Alternate Function 9 (AF9)) */
		pinctrl-0 = <&can2_rx_pb12 &can2_tx_pb13>;

		/* Configure pins as analog in sleep mode */
		pinctrl-1 = <&can2_sleep_pb12 &can2_sleep_pb13>;

		status = "okay"; /* Enable CAN2 */
	};

	/* Enable mailbox for OpenAMP */
	&mailbox {
		status = "okay"; /* Enable mailbox */
	};

	/* Enable CAN1 and CAN2 */
	can1_rx_pa11: can1_rx_pa11 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('A', 11, AF9)>; /* PA11 -> CAN1_RX */
		bias-disable; /* Turns off internal pull-up or pull-down resistor */
	};
	can1_tx_pa12: can1_tx_pa12 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('A', 12, AF9)>; /* PA12 -> CAN1_TX */
		bias-disable; /* Turns off internal pull-up or pull-down resistor */
		drive-push-pull; /* Pin output driver to actively drive both high and low levels rather then open drain or open source */
	};
	
	/* Low power (sleep) state: pins as analog */
	can1_sleep_pa11: can1_sleep_pa11 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('A', 11, ANALOG)>;
	}; 
	can1_sleep_pa12: can1_sleep_pa12 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('A', 12, ANALOG)>;
	};

	/* FDCAN2 Pin assignments */
	can2_rx_pb12: can2_rx_pb12 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('B', 12, AF9)>; /* PB12 -> CAN2_RX */
		bias-disable; /* Turns off internal pull-up or pull-down resistor */
	};
	can2_tx_pb13: can2_tx_pb13 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('B', 13, AF9)>; /* PB13 -> CAN2_TX */
		bias-disable; /* Turns off internal pull-up or pull-down resistor */
		drive-push-pull; /* Pin output driver to actively drive both high and low levels rather then open drain or open source */
	};
	
	/* Low power (sleep) state: pins as analog */
	can2_sleep_pb12: can2_sleep_pb12 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('B', 12, ANALOG)>;
	}; 
	can2_sleep_pb13: can1_sleep_pb13 {
		pinmux = <STM32_PINMUX('B', 13, ANALOG)>;
	};
	
	```

from that point forward i also made a main.c file to see if my LED would blink:
â¯ cat firmware/src/main.c
#include <zephyr/kernel.h>
#include <zephyr/device.h>
#include <zephyr/2drivers/gpio.h>

#define LED_PORT DT_LABEL(DT_NODELABEL(gpioa))
#define LED_PIN 13

void main(void)
{
    const struct device *led_dev;
    int ret;

    led_dev = device_get_binding(LED_PORT);
    if (led_dev == NULL) {
        printk("Failed to get LED device binding\n");
        return;
    }

    ret = gpio_pin_configure(led_dev, LED_PIN, GPIO_OUTPUT_ACTIVE);
    if (ret < 0) {
        printk("Failed to configure LED pin\n");
        return;
    }

    while (1) {
        gpio_pin_toggle(led_dev, LED_PIN);
        k_msleep(500);
    }
}



This was incorrect handling of the file though so i made this:
```C
#include <zephyr/kernel.h>
#include <zephyr/device.h>
#include <zephyr/drivers/gpio.h>


// led0 from alias tree in 'zephyr/boards/st/stm32mp157c_dk2/stm32mp157c_dk2.dts'
#define LED0_NODE DT_ALIAS(led0)

// GPIO specification for led0
static const struct gpio_dt_spec led0 = GPIO_DT_SPEC_GET(LED0_NODE, gpios);

void main(void)
{
    if (!device_is_ready(led0.port)) {
        // Device is not ready, handle the error
        printk("Error: %s device is not ready\n", led0.port->name);
        return;
    }

    // Configure the GPIO pin as output
    gpio_pin_configure_dt(&led0, GPIO_OUTPUT_LOW);

    // Blink the LED in a loop
    while (1) {
        // Turn the LED on
        gpio_pin_set_dt(&led0, 1);
        k_msleep(500);

        // Turn the LED off
        gpio_pin_set_dt(&led0, 0);
        k_msleep(500);
    }
    
    
}

```
Because in the device tree structure the alias is led0

Then I would run:
```C
west update
west build -b stm32mp157c_dk2 firmware/
```
and once we have the build file, i would flash the .elf file by running:
west flash -d build -r openocd --elf-file build/zephyr/zephyr.elf --use-elf --verify
